When it comes to scaling DFI on Ethereum, we have quite a few options either already available or not being too far from a full launch. These options belong to one of the two categories layer two scaling and sidechains. Layer two scaling, relies on the security of the main layer. The ethereum blockchain. Sidechains rely on their own security models, usually by having a separate consensus mechanism. They can also have additional security guarantees that leverage the main layer. But despite this, they're usually considered less secure than layer two solutions. One of the most discussed layer two options when it comes to DeFi are rollups. Rollups provide scaling by executing transactions outside of layer one, but posting transaction data on layer one, which allows rollapps to be secured by the main Ethereum chain. There are two types of rollups optimistic rollapps and ZK rollaps. Optimistic rollups run an EVM compatible virtual machine which allows for executing the same smart contracts as on Ethereum.
